  "prompt": "Why does the intensity of light become half when a lens is cut horizontally but not if cut perpendicular to principal axis?",
  "response": "The behavior of light when a lens is cut depends on the way the lens affects the area through which light can pass. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. **Cutting the Lens Horizontally:**\n    - When a lens is cut horizontally, you essentially halve the lens along a plane parallel to the principal axis. This reduces the overall area of the lens that is capable of transmitting light.\n    - Assume we start with a lens where the entire aperture lets light through. If we cut the lens horizontally, the effective area lets half the amount of light through compared to the whole lens.\n    - As a result, the intensity of light passing through the lens is reduced to half because intensity is directly proportional to the area through which the light can pass.\n\n2. **Cutting the Lens Perpendicular to the Principal Axis:**\n    - Cutting the lens perpendicularly through the principal axis divides the lens into two symmetrical halves. Each piece still retains the same ability to focus light.\n    - The total area through which light can pass is not reduced; rather, you have two identical halves that can still focus the light similarly into single points (central point).\n    - Thus, if you were to use each half independently, they each still utilize the full initial light intensity directed towards them. When considering the lens as a whole, the focusing characteristics remain essentially the same, and there is no reduction in the overall intensity of the light.\n\nTo summarize, when a lens is cut horizontally (parallel to the principal axis), the overall effective area through which light can pass is reduced, which halves the light intensity. However, when cut perpendicularly to the principal axis, the focusing functionality and effective area remain the same, so the light intensity does not change.",
